mwB3Y">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwB3c">1 January</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Charlemagne&amp;rft.btitle=Icons+of+the+Middle+Ages%3A+Rulers%2C+Writers%2C+Rebels%2C+and+Saints&amp;rft.place=Santa+Barbara%2C+California&amp;rft.pages=143-74+172&amp;rft.pub=Greenwood&amp;rft.date=2012&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-313-34080-2&amp;rft.aulast=Hoche&amp;rft.aufirst=Dominique+T&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DrETxD8KcnUIC%26pg%3DPA172&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharlemagne" class="Z3988" about="#mwt771" id="mwB3g"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt771" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwB3k"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-148" id="cite_note-148"><a href="./Charlemagne#cite_ref-148" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-148" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Arthurian-legend" id="mwB3o">Arthurian Legend — Encyclopedia Brittanica</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-149" id="cite_note-149"><a href="./Charlemagne#cite_ref-149" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-149" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt777" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite book","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"{{google books |plainurl=y |id=pnxdCwAAQBAJ|page=44}}"},"title":{"wt":"Arthur: King of Britain"},"last":{"wt":"Fraley"},"first":{"wt":"Michael"},"date":{"wt":"1993-08-14"},"publisher":{"wt":"Caliber Comics"},"isbn":{"wt":"9781626657984"},"language":{"wt":"en"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwB3s">Fraley, Michael (1993-08-14). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=pnxdCwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA44" id="mwB3w"><i id="mwB30">Arthur: King of Britain</i></a>. Caliber Comics. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwB34">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwB38"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/9781626657984" title="Special:BookSources/9781626657984" id="mwB4A">9781626657984</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Arthur%3A+King+of+Britain&amp;rft.pub=Caliber+Comics&amp;rft.date=1993-08-14&amp;rft.isbn=9781626657984&amp;rft.aulast=Fraley&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DpnxdCwAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPA44&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharlemagne" class="Z3988" about="#mwt777" id="mwB4E"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt777" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwB4I"/><br id="mwB4M"/>"To anyone familiar with the early Medieval Period of European history, Geoffrey's story begins to sound familiar here. It should. It seems to be based, in large part, on the historical adventures of Charlemagne, the Frankish King of the Ninth Century, who eventually became Emperor. Looking at Charlemagne's life and personality, it becomes clear that he and Geoffrey's Arthur are practically twins."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-150" id="cite_note-150"><a href="./Charlemagne#cite_ref-150" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-150" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.mementomedievalia.com/charlemagne-king-arthur-and-contested-national-identity-in-english-romances/" id="mwB4Q">Charlemagne, King Arthur and Contested National Identity in English Romances</a><br id="mwB4U"/> Modelling his narrative on earlier Middle English texts, the English AMA-poet, appropriates aspects of the historical reality of Charlemagne and refashions them to fit Arthur, creating a hero that the English can claim as their own.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-DLS17-151" id="cite_note-DLS17-151"><a href="./Charlemagne#cite_ref-DLS17_151-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-DLS17-151" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dorothy_L._Sayers" title="Dorothy L. Sayers" id="mwB4Y">Dorothy L. Sayers</a>, <i id="mwB4c">Paradise</i>, notes on Canto XVII.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-cgt-152" id="cite_note-cgt-152"><a href="./Charlemagne#cite_ref-cgt_152-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-cgt-152" class="mw-reference-text">Banham (1998, 678).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-153" id="cite_note-153"><a href="./Charlemagne#cite_ref-153" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-153" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt789" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://www.supremecourt.gov/about/northandsouthwalls.pdf"},"title":{"wt":"US Supreme Court Courtroom Friezes"},"accessdate":{"wt":"19 February 2019"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwB4g"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/about/northandsouthwalls.pdf" id="mwB4k">"US Supreme Court Courtroom Friezes"</a> <span class="cs1-format" id="mwB4o">(PDF)</span><span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwB4s">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwB4w">19 February</span> 2019</span>.</cite><s